2/52
there’s a lot going on in my head. 

this is my last week here at home ( moving back to LA next week ). for the past 8 months this has felt like the right decision, i was really unhappy being back in NY because my mind was somewhere else. i had this uneasy feeling of unfinished business. 

mix that with the first time acknowledging and struggling with my mental health makes this week a lot worse than i thought it would be.

what scares me is leaving behind the people i love and the unknown. for the very first time i don’t have a full time job, and I’ve never been confident enough to be a full time photographer because the unknown gives me crippling anxiety. everyone keeps saying that you’ll figure it out, you always have. i wish i had the same confidence they have in me. 

maybe this is an over share. this isn’t a cry for help either, i just need a place to let out these feelings. if anyone else is struggling and afraid to share, know you’re not alone. 🫡❤️

we put together another global team for @thespeedproject . paris montreal amsterdam jakarta los angeles and new york were represented this year. 

aside from making it to las vegas safely the goal is simple, bring together a group of people who never really met each other with the only thing in common which is running. the beauty of this is no matter the language barrier or background, the team came together and became inseparable by the end of the weekend. no matter if you crewed ran or took photos you are all part of making our vision come to life.

boston through the years

2017
2018
2022… are some of my favorite years that i’ve covered

i got a big push in my career as a photographer because of crew culture. no matter how hectic the finish line assignments are i always try to make it to cheer-zone no matter where i am whether it’s grabbing a citi bike to uptown an uber to heartbreak hill riding around in a vespa lost in berlin with @biznezninja because we can’t read the street signs or grabbing the tube to limehouse.

excited to head out back east be home for a bit and cover yet another boston marathon.

a few that didn’t make the cut.

2018 i got the honor to shoot my first global campaign for nike as a last minute addition to a incredibly talented photo and video team. 

5 days in Kenya getting to document one of this sport’s greatest athletes. 

since then I’ve had the privilege of following him around at marathons like Berlin and London. 

excited to watch him put together another beautiful race here in Boston!

the night before.
🦄

after the elites finish i always make my way down to the run crew cheer zone to show support to a community of runners who have trained just as hard. i’ve been blessed enough to cover every major marathon where we always have a cheer zone for our run crews. and i can confidently say i’ve never witnessed what i’ve seen today.

we were trying to to make the best of the situation with the weather conditions. energy was high, we were grilling, playing music, and lifting spirits at the top of a hard hill. all of that was stifled when a large group of boston police officers roll by, push people back, and threaten to arrest people if they step foot on the pavement again. they then surrounded the cheer zone for over 15 minutes preventing crew members from cheering 

as much as we try to grow the sport, moments like this make us feel like we don’t belong. 

today was still special. the marathon and the energy continued despite the actions of some, but i don’t want to ignore that this happened and it only serves as a reminder that there is still work to be done in this sport

today marks my first year as a full time freelancer. I’ve been freelancing for over 12 years now but always with the support of a full time job.

it’s been a rough year to be honest. but reflecting back i’ve still gotten to travel quite a bit with some of my favorite people that i hold near to my heart. i finally get to work on projects that i want to do. but the down time kills me.

this last year i realized how much of my self worth is attached to the work i do and honestly it’s a shitty feeling. that mixed with knowing you have some anxiety and dealing with depression is a recipe for your thoughts to get out of control. 

if you haven’t noticed i also moved back across the country to LA 🙃 and at least once a week i ask myself wtf am i doing here and what was i running away from. but in spite of that i’m so thankful for the community i’ve been building here from krc to guys at the gym every monday morning. you all are little by little bringing me back to the old me.

at apple they used to tell us putting yourself in uncomfortable situations leads to growth. they should warn you that it comes with a lot of ass kicks along the way. but sometimes you have to have blind faith when gambling on yourself.

berlin through the years… tomorrow looks a little different

for years i watched some of my closest friends go out and crush this race. i’ve followed elites through that 26.2 mile journey and be inspired not only by there performances but by their journey that gets them to the start line.

i haven’t ran a marathon since Chicago 2019. that marathon really fucked me up and i was too scared to get back out there. to the point that i completely stopped running. in the most recent years i’ve been struggling with my mental health and found that movement and running once again puts my mind at ease once I’m done (during is a different story).

am i ready for tomorrow?
absolutely not. i haven’t ran much since 2019 and just started running again  in april. 
am i still traumatized from chicago? 
absolutely.

i am beyond scared for what i am about to go through tomorrow and honestly wasn’t really sure if i wanted to share this post. i didn’t want to add pressure to myself, but the mood of: let go let god took over

i can’t go without saying thanks to @bitbeefy @jules_buena @gjdame and @fitandfullbykayla . have i listened to all your suggestions and coaching? that’s a different story but thanks for making time, getting me to the start line and getting me to run again. that last one honestly that’s the biggest win regardless of what happens tomorrow. ❤️

yes that’s an inhaler on top of my singlet

@oldmanrunclub ❤️

#QGTM

i should’ve just been out there shooting.

listen it was rough out there.
a lot of people told me not to run this marathon i needed more time to train. do it next year.

ya’ll were right. 🥴 but the thing about me is that i don’t like to fail when i set my mind towards something. 

i wanted to quit so many times today but for my mental health I’m glad i didn’t. 

shirt came off at one point channeling my inner @hecisdead and started to crawl back @cliiish thanks for pulling me out of the gutter that second half of the marathon i don’t know what the day would’ve been if it wasn’t for you

@ted_deluxe thank you for being the first person i saw as i crossed the finish line it meant the world to me that you waited out there. 

berlin you also lied def felt some hills out there in the 3k and somewhere around 10k 🙄 but thank you for the ass kick today

thanks for the the 1 pic inspo @lord_edwin

someone tell me where to get a new plantar tho

@alina_bueno_ and @bru_knowz thank you for having us be a part of your new chapter in your life. I would’ve traveled anywhere in the world for you two to watch you celebrate your love.

leaving with a heart full spending time exploring and being with the people that i value most in life.

thank you guys again for a wonder few days! ❤️

@notafraid2fail was on the top of my list of people to follow today. Love you bro. Got to see you in the beginning and at the end. ❤️❤️

I have admired @notafraid2fail work for years. It seemed like Jason had it all. Incredible talent as a photographer, all the opportunities a creator could ever want, and a strong, close community to share adventures with.

Of course, as with everything, it is not always what it seems. Jason and I had a vulnerable and raw conversation about what the world sees vs what is actually going on behind the scenes. This has been a big year for both of us, but as with everything, it’s not the full story.

Find the episode of @runningforreal on your favorite podcast player or at runningforreal.com/episode380

starting to figure out LA a little bit i’ve realized it’s a reset i needed in my life i’m a little healthier out here i mean your boy is going on hikes now when things get stressful now.
